The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
Archives
				 Project cost funds okayed
 A STAFF REPORTER																								The state government on Wednesday sanctioned Rs 122 crore for the East-West Metro project as its share of the hike in cost.																								The estimated project cost has gone up from Rs 4,310 crore to Rs 5,165 crore.																								The latest estimate has taken into account cost escalation, as well as interest on loan, said additional chief secretary (transport) Sumantra Chowdhury.																								According to the revised calculation, the state and Centre have to shell out Rs 1,100 crore each, while the Japan Bank for International Cooperation (JBIC) will provide a soft loan of Rs 2,900 crore.																								An appraisal team from the JBIC is in town and is looking into various aspects of the project before deciding to fund it. The team is focussing on environmental hazards and a rehabilitation policy for those who will be displaced by the project.																								The team will inform the government about its conclusions in November-end, said an official.																								The 13.77-km East-West Metro route stretches from Salt Lakes Central Park to Howrah station, with stations at Sealdah and Writers Buildings, among other places. The project is scheduled to be completed in 2014.																								The state is readying to make a presentation before the finance ministrys Public Investment Board, which vets all investments of over Rs 100 crore by the Centre. 
